I'll help you create a new knowledge graph based on the provided schema and example. I'll create different types of nodes with meaningful relationships and clear documentation.

```turtle
@prefix dcterms: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix sc: <http://pygraf.t/> .

# Ontology declaration
sc: a owl:Ontology ;
    dcterms:license <https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/> .

# Hub Node - Central entity with many connections
sc:Organization1 a sc:C10 ;
    rdfs:label "Main Organization" ;
    rdfs:comment "A hub organization connecting multiple departments" ;
    sc:R1 sc:Department1, sc:Department2, sc:Department3 ;
    sc:R3 sc:Project1, sc:Project2 ;
    sc:R4 sc:Team1, sc:Team2 ;
    sc:R6 sc:Location1 .

# High-degree Node - Multiple relationships of different types
sc:Department1 a sc:C9 ;
    rdfs:label "Research Department" ;
    rdfs:comment "Department handling research activities" ;
    sc:R2 sc:Project1 ;
    sc:R4 sc:Team1 ;
    sc:R9 sc:Department2, sc:Department3 .

# Central Node - Key connection point
sc:Project1 a sc:C2 ;
    rdfs:label "Core Project" ;
    rdfs:comment "Main project connecting multiple teams" ;
    sc:R10 sc:Team1, sc:Team2 ;
    sc:R5 sc:Department2, sc:Department3 .

# Connector Node - Bridges different components
sc:Team1 a sc:C6 ;
    rdfs:label "Integration Team" ;
    rdfs:comment "Team responsible for system integration" ;
    sc:R7 sc:Project2, sc:Location1 .

# Intermediary Node - Facilitates connections
sc:Department2 a sc:C5 ;
    rdfs:label "Development Department" ;
    rdfs:comment "Department coordinating development activities" ;
    sc:R2 sc:Project2 ;
    sc:R9 sc:Team2 .

# Multiplex Node - Multiple relationships of same type
sc:Location1 a sc:C1 ;
    rdfs:label "Main Office" ;
    rdfs:comment "Primary business location" ;
    sc:R1 sc:Team1, sc:Team2, sc:Department3 .

# Super Node - High centrality and influence
sc:Project2 a sc:C3 ;
    rdfs:label "Strategic Initiative" ;
    rdfs:comment "Key strategic project with broad impact" ;
    sc:R3 sc:Team1, sc:Team2 ;
    sc:R4 sc:Department1, sc:Department2 .

# Supporting Nodes
sc:Department3 a sc:C8 ;
    rdfs:label "Operations Department" ;
    rdfs:comment "Department managing operational activities" ;
    sc:R9 sc:Team1, sc:Team2 .

sc:Team2 a sc:C4 ;
    rdfs:label "Implementation Team" ;
    rdfs:comment "Team handling system implementation" ;
    sc:R1 sc:Project1 ;
    sc:R6 sc:Location1 .
```

This knowledge graph represents an organizational structure with different departments, projects, teams, and locations. I've created various types of nodes:

1. Hub Node (Organization1): Central entity with multiple connections
2. High-degree Node (Department1): Multiple diverse relationships
3. Central Node (Project1): Key connection point
4. Connector Node (Team1): Bridges different components
5. Intermediary Node (Department2): Facilitates connections
6. Multiplex Node (Location1): Multiple similar relationships
7. Super Node (Project2): High influence and centrality

Each node has meaningful labels and comments, and all relationships follow the schema constraints. The graph demonstrates different relationship types (R1-R10) and class hierarchies (C1-C10).